Although the PL intensity of CPDs continuously decreased with varying Fe3+ concentrations (0.1–1.0 μM), the linear equation produces was y = 0.2320x+0.0099, R2 = 0.998, and the limit of detection (LOD) stood at 0.05 μM (Fig. S7). By comparing the detection limits of various CDs, we confirmed the superior Fe3+ sensitivity of Re-CPDs. (

                           Table 1


                        ).

Re-CPDs were subjected to various concentrations of Mo6+ (0–25 μM) to verify the sensitivity of Re-CPDs to Mo6+ by monitoring the change of PL intensity at 461 nm (Fig. S11). As depicted in Fig. 4
                        a, the PL intensity of Re-CPDs reached its maximum at 9 μM with increasing Mo6+ content. The fluorescence intensity changes in response to Mo6+ (0–9 μM) are shown in Fig. 4b, and a linear equation with R2 = 0.992 and y = 0.04912x+1.00056 was successfully fitted by the F/F0 equation between Mo6+ concentration (1–9 μM) and PL intensity, resulting in a limit of detection (LOD) for Mo6+ of 0.48 μM. On the other hand, the addition of Mo6+ (0–10 μM) to CPDs did not result in a regular variation in PL intensity (Fig. S12). Comparison with previous studies on the limit of detection (LOD) of Mo6+ (Table 2
                        ) demonstrated the excellent sensitivity of Re-CPDs to Mo6+.

The detection of metal ions in milk is of great significance for human health, environmental protection, and industrial production. To ensure the accuracy and stability of Re-CPDs in real samples, we treated milk according to the experimental section and added different concentrations (0.2, 0.6, and 1.0 μM) of Fe3+ ions for experiments (

                           Table 3


                        ). Similarly, experiments were conducted under the same conditions using the same experimental method with different concentrations (1.0, 4.0, and 6.0 μM) of Mo6+ ions in milk samples (

                           Table 4


                        ). After testing, the spiked content was found to be highly fitted to the tested content, and the recoveries of Fe3+ and Mo6+ ions were 98.6% and 102.3%, respectively. In summary, Re-CPDs are a convenient, accurate, stable, and environmentally friendly new nano-sensing material.
